                <head>271. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On September 30, <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> Secretary General
                        <persName corresp="#p_SPH1">Spaak</persName> introduced a draft statement on
                    Cyprus in the North Atlantic Council. The Spaak statement, as modified by the
                    Council, noted <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> concern with the ongoing
                    dispute in Cyprus and endorsed the presence of the Turkish representative on
                    Cyprus within the limited role assigned him under the <persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        >Macmillan</persName> Plan. The statement also reiterated the desirability
                    of a three-power conference on Cyprus. For text of the Spaak paper, see The
                    Cyprus Question, pages 10–11. Spaak’s version of the meeting is in Combats
                    Inacheves, <ref target="frus1958-60v02#pg_151">volume II, pages 151</ref>–<ref
                        target="frus1958-60v02#pg_154">154</ref>.</p>
            </div>
